datastring.name: Additional Information Clarification:
datastring.dstemplatestring:
Johnson & Johnson Consumer, Inc. is submitting this report pursuant to the provisions of 21 CFR, Part 803. This report may be
based on information which Johnson & Johnson Consumer, Inc. has not been able to investigate or verify prior to the required
reporting date. This report does not reflect a conclusion by FDA, Johnson & Johnson Consumer, Inc. or its employees that the
report constitutes an admission that the device, Johnson & Johnson Consumer, Inc., or its employees caused or contributed to the
potential event described in this report.

Device was used for treatment, not diagnosis.

This report is a serious adverse event for drug component (TYLENOL INFANTS 100MG/ML SUSPENSION DROPS FRUIT). The
device component (Oral Syringe) is assessed as a reportable event due to adverse event with use error of device. This report is
serious adverse event and reportable serious injury.

Device evaluation/investigation could not be completed; No conclusion could be drawn as product was not returned to
manufacturer. An analysis of packaging and labelling was conducted.

Effective on Apr-23-2020 the Syringe was validated to not have the measurement of mL and Kg but only in mL on the Syringe. The
Packaging states: TYLENOL Baby: for correct dosage, administer the dose of medication according to the child's weight and
volume (mL) indicated on the metering syringe. The Packaging Insert states: TYLENOL Baby: for correct dosage, administer the
dose of the drug according to the child's weight and the corresponding volume (mL) indicated on the syringe dosing device. As

datastring.name: Additional Manufacture Narrative
datastring.dstemplatestring:
A Sales Representative Reported: “In one of the medical visitations, the physician reported to me an event regarding the syringe
used in the dosage of baby Tylenol that caught my attention. The absence of weight together with ml in the syringe. A mother
medicated her baby who has 5kg with 3ml of Tylenol baby, once the physician who Is used to the prescription of the product
prescribed it. As there was no more time because it had been 2 hours since the baby had been medicated and the physician could
not induce vomiting, the baby had hypothermia. The physician mentioned the difficulty of prescribing with the syringe without
including weight and ml and prefers to stop prescribing. Is there a possibility to return the syringe with both measures?. No
further information was provided.”
